Reference-contexts: With the allocation of the Industrial, Scientific, and Medical (ISM) bands for unlicensed use in 1985, came great enthusiasm for commercial use of WLAN products in these bands [2]. By 1990, the first ISM band WLAN products came out on the market <ref> [3] </ref>. Soon after, the IEEE 802.11 committee was formed and began work on a standard for high speed WLANs. The 2.4GHz ISM band was chosen for a worldwide WLAN RF standard by the 802.11 committee because it was globally available. <p> The development of the standard began in 1990, when the IEEE 802.11 WLAN committee was formed <ref> [3] </ref>. Their goal was to create a standard for WLAN which would allow high data rates 1 as well as interoperabilty among different WLAN products operating in the same medium. The fifth draft of the 802.11 standard has recently been accepted bringing 802.11 close to completion.
