Reference-contexts: The MAC specification of 802.11 provides asynchronous, time-bounded and contention free access through different physical layers. The MAC is implemented using a Carrier Sense Multiple Access/Collision Avoidance (CSMA/CA) protocol <ref> [4] </ref>. The PHY layer provides access through either an infrared or RF medium. Finally, the MAC-PHY sublayers define the structure of 802.11 packets [5]. The 802.11 standard specifies three physical layer transmission methods: Diffused Infrared (DFIR), Direct Sequence Spread Spectrum (DSSS), and Frequency Hopping Spread Spectrum (FHSS). <p> Connections between different BSS's or to a wired network are accomplished by using an Access Point (AP). The CF which allows BSS communications is implemented in the physical layer of the network. It utilizes a physical property of the medium to separate different BSS's from one another <ref> [4] </ref>. In the DSSS specification, the CF is implemented by breaking up the 2.4GHz transmission band into 11 channels 2 , each with a unique center frequency [5]. For transmission in any channel the 11 bit Barker sequence has been specified.
